The Cdots films were undergo tartrazine adsorption to study the feasibility of immobilization of fluorescent Cdots. All 3 films showed slight reduction in light transmittance after tartrazine adsorption (Fig. 7
                     ), however, PVA/PEG showed no changes in fluorescent intensity as Cdots was absent in this film. By comparing the fluorescence emission spectra of PVA/Cdots and PVA/PEG/Cdots thin films to the fluorescence emission spectrum of PVA/PEG thin film, the presence of Cdots in PVA/Cdots and PVA/PEG/Cdots thin films was confirmed by the significant growth of fluorescent intensity. Both PVA/CDOT and PVA/PEG/CDOT showed a reduction of fluorescent intensity after tartrazine adsorption, indicating the presence of tartazine and the success of developing fluorescent thin films as sensor. Other works [14,18] reported on the fluorescence decays of Cdots in thin film and in solution as well. However, the mechanism of the enhanced fluorescent property is still under debate [14] as mentioned earlier. Static quenching was proposed by Xu et al. [7] and Theodoros [20] highlighted that IFE could also contributed into the sensing of tartrazine. Since PVA/Cdots and PVA/PEG/Cdots thin films are transparent, the Cdots are expected to excite, and emit lights during sensing as illustrated in Fig. 8
                     . The LOD of PVA/Cdots thin film was calculated to be 28.55 μM which is very high compared to LOD values reported by others, namely 73 nM [7] and 200 nM [20]. The great difference might be due to the high concentration of Cdot in polymeric thin film, which requires 1% of light transmittance setting to detect the fluorescence intensity. Hence, the detection of tartrazine using PVA/Cdots nanocomposite films is still limited by the concentration of Cdot in the film, mass transfer and adsorption of the tartrazine. These issues should be further studied prior to the development of practical sensors using PVA/Cdots.
